			<ul class="comment b2" id="comment-6404545">
				
				<li class="comment-author"   >
                    
                        <div class="badges">
                            
                                



                            
                        </div>
                        <div class="profile" >
                            
                                
<img src="http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/site_furniture/2010/09/01/no-user-image.gif" height="60" width="60" alt="" />
<a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/discussion/user/Flyswot" title="User profile page">Flyswot</a>

                            
                            <p class="date">14 October 2009 7:09PM</p>
                        </div>
                    
					<div class="comment-body">
						
							<p>This, if true, is absolutely marvellous, and will make my head swell even more in the knowledge that as a life long Guardian reader I've always been buying the right paper.</p><p>Being a proper, fair-minded Guardianista, I've taken a look at the other side of the story.  It's here:  <a href="http://www.carter-ruck.com/Documents/Trafigura-Press_Release-13.10.2009.pdf"><a href="http://www.carter-ruck.com/Documents/Trafigura-Press_Release-13.10.2009.pdf">http://www.carter-ruck.com/Documents/Trafigura-Press_Release-13.10.2009.pdf</a></a>  Why not take a look and decide for yourselves?</p><p>If it's right that what happened was 1) an order was framed in wide terms without any contemplation of a parliamentary impact 2) the width was such to cover a parliamentary questions (I guess it was just a blanket prohibition), 3) this was pointed out to Carter Ruck who (as they are obliged to) sought their clients instructions regarding variation and then 4) agreed to a variation (I can't decide if they did this slowly - noon the next day is 3-4 working hours later, but I expect there's a hotline)... then my outrage turns on the Guardian for sickeningly inaccurate tabloidesque grandstanding over an issue of fundamental importance.  I really hope not; the Independent is just too dull.</p><p>It might well be that the original order should not have been granted.  I know none of the details.  I do know the story has not been reported on that basis - it's all been on the basis that Carter Ruck gagged Parliament, or that a judge did.  Are either actually true?</p>
						
					</div>
				</li>
				
