					<div class="comment-body">
						
							<p>As far as the carrot and stick analogy goes, it should also be remembered how those can also be used by the people at large.</p><p>Distillers successfully managed to legally prevent The Sunday Times' Insight team from publishing information about thalidomide and the fact that the company was not paying compensation to victims and was effectively fiddling the medical evidence.</p><p>It was only when John Pilger spoke to Ralph Nader about boycotting Distillers' products in America that the company finally caved in.</p><p>It seems that it only found a conscience when it saw the possibility of vast amounts of money flowing from its coffers and leaving the cupboard bare for its directors and shareholders.</p><p>For those who imagine that the law is there to protect them from abuses of power, it is also there to assist those who wish to abuse power.</p><p>For those who think information is power, there are some starting points about Trafigura here:</p><p><a href="http://news.google.co.uk/news/more?um=1&amp;cf=all&amp;ned=uk&amp;cf=all&amp;ncl=dyDsU1FhyuuQ--MfiH7tHvPhXp7oM">http://news.google.co.uk/news/more?um=1&amp;cf=all&amp;ned=uk&amp;cf=all&amp;ncl=dyDsU1FhyuuQ--MfiH7tHvPhXp7oM</a></p><p>and here:</p><p><a href="http://blogsearch.google.co.uk/blogsearch?q=trafigura&amp;hl=en&amp;ie=UTF-8&amp;tab=nb">http://blogsearch.google.co.uk/blogsearch?q=trafigura&amp;hl=en&amp;ie=UTF-8&amp;tab=nb</a></p>
						
