							<p>I think the Guardian had done well in this parrticular instance but advise against supporters of the notion on a free press from getting too carried away.</p><p>1)  Private Eye as been bravely doing this sort of stuff for decades - all on its own and with far less resources than a paper like this one.  (It was Private Eye for example that first broke the scandals involving BAE systems ALMOST 6 YEARS AGO before anyone took notice.  There is an ongoing scandal involving the CDC that the Private Eye has been follwoing for more than 2 years now that no other paper seems to want to touch. )  SO WHY CANT THIS PAPER BE AS ACTIVE AS THE PRIVATE EYE IN CHASING DOWN ALL CORRUPTION.</p><p>2) That judges do issue the so-called super-injunction orders is for me the real issue.  That this sort of action can actually take place under legal sanction is truly frighteneing.   This aspect more than anything else and is worhty of a thorough investigation .</p><p>3)  The whole issue seems to be linked inextricably to the UK's draconian libe l and criminal defamation laws which, with the full support of the juduciary, makes it very very difficult for anyone to expose currupt practice, general wrong doing and the hypocritical posturing of public figures. </p>
						
