					<div class="comment-body">
						
							<p>Nice story.</p><p>Shame it doesn't appear to be true.</p><p>What <a href="http://www.carter-ruck.com/Documents/Trafigura-Press_Release-13.10.2009.pdf">seems to have happened</a> is:</p><p>(a) Trifigura obtained an injunction to prevent the reporting of a confidential document (with no mention or thought that it might be raised in Parliament);</p><p>(b) the Guardian consent to that injunction being maintained until trial;</p><p>(c) a question is asked in Parliament;</p><p>(d) Carter-Ruck take the (rather dubious - but presumably arguable) position that the injunction is in sufficiently wide terms as to prevent the reporting of that question;</p><p>(e) the Guardian agrees with that interpretation and seeks to vary the injunction so as to make specific provision excepting parliamentary reporting from the ambit of the injunction;</p><p>(f) Trifigura respond by saying that they will take instructions;</p><p>(g) Guardian publishes;</p><p>(h) CR agrees to an amendment to the order to make it plain that it does not prevent parliamentary matters from being reported.</p><p>So, we have:</p><p>(a) no court or lawyer which has sought to injunct Parliament;</p><p>(b0 a situation whereby, far from kicking and screaming against this "super" injunction, the Guardian meekly consented to it; and</p><p>(c) no apparent role whatsoever in this affair for these blogs and twits who supposedly broke the story.</p><p>Yet you would not know any of this from this article. In fact, you would get completely the opposite impression!</p><p>And people are supposed to be willing to trust the <i>media </i>to decide what they should be allowed to publish when they can't even accurately report on things which they have an intimate knowledge of?</p><p>Physicians heal thyselves.</p>
						
					</div>
				</li>
				
