                        </div>
                    
					<div class="comment-body">
						
							<p>Well done Guardian.  I dont know why but the paper seems, in this and other ways, to be getting more radical, libertarian and investigative as time goes on.  Please keep up the excellent work.</p><p>I have no special reason to defend the Carter-Ruck firm, and certainly not for their odious Trafigura clients (complete with Tory peers on the board).  But could we be clear that if too-oppressive injunctions are being granted by the courts, and parliamentary liberties eaten into, this is not the fault of Trafigura's solicitors.  Carter-Ruck have a clear professional duty to do the best for their clients, by pursuing any legal argument which has a realistic prospect of success (whether or not it actually succeeds).</p><p>The fault is with the courts or parliament, both of which could act to make these injunctions somewhat less 'super' (ie oppressive).  This would not be straightforward for parliament because so much of injunction law is judge made, but in theory it could be done.</p>
						
					</div>
